featured_reviews.review_translated_text:
Shaheed Kunhi Marakkar was one of the brave patriots of Malabar who declared a no-cease struggle against the western occupation forces. Some of the members of Malik ibn Dinar's group married the natives of the places where they preached and the first Muslim houses sprang up there. A family home in Chalia is a family home in Mammasrailat. Kunjimarakar was born in this family as Abdullah's son.

When I was young, my parents moved from Chaliat to Veliyangto Manathuparam. He memorized the Qur'an at an early age under the guidance of his parents. He also studied sports as per the custom of that time. He grew up under the care of his mother after his father died at the age of 10.

One day, he called his twelve-year-old son, gave him some money and told him to buy fish and start a business. Zainuddin Makhdoom happened to see Ponnani when he was walking by the large Jumu'ah mosque during the fish trade. Makhdoom called the children and hugged them and kissed them on the forehead.
Then he said, "This holy head is not for carrying fish baskets." It is the dome of faith. He was immediately given good clothes and sent home.

Abdul Qadir Shaikh, who was next to Makhdoom, curiously asked Zainuddin Makhdoom about the secret of the said boy. Makhdoom said. This standing figure has an exquisite heritage face. The sanctity to be adorned with the highest rank among the Siddhas is vested in this child even at this time. This boy who becomes a martyr who sacrifices his life for the sake of Islamic visions and their survival deserves all our love and respect. The world will always praise him for his selfless services.
Kunjimarakar who came home told the story of what happened to Umma. Following her wish, she lived with Makhdoom for the rest of her life with her mother's consent. Under Makhdoom's tutelage, Kunjimarakar became a scholar and arif.

During his lifetime Kunjimarakar sacrificed his life fighting against the Portuguese who extended their evil hands towards Kerala. In the book Mapila Malabar, Dr Hussain Randathani describes the martyrdom of the Kunjimaras as follows.
On the day of the wedding, the exciting news reaches the ears of Kunjimarakar. Parangi natives have arrived in Malabar. They are on a killing spree, killing the people. Two more people have abducted a Muslim girl. Kunji caught the heart of the trees. He came out of the marriage hall on the pretense of urinating. He went to see his mother and took blessings. Hanging his sword on his waist, he went to the sea shore and got into a canoe and rowed towards the ship which was parked at a distance.

It is very late at night
Kunjimarakar jumped into the ship. Everyone is drunk and asleep. Kunjimarakar made everyone happy. The girl was rescued. Kunjimarakar returned to the sea aiming for another ship. Those on this ship were also killed. But only one person was standing out of sight of the trees. He slashed with his sword. The tree fell and became a martyr. His dead body was cut into seven pieces and thrown into the sea. It is said that those parts were washed away in many places and graves were made in all those places. Kunjimarakars would be the first martyrs who laid down their lives against the European invasion.

The graves of the Kunjimaras are located in Veliyangode, Tanur, Meenchantha (Kotupalli), Vadakara, Beypur, Vypin and Kota.
